{"title_page": "Oysterville Cemetery", "text_new": "\n\n[[File:Oysterville cemetery sign.jpg|thumb|Wooden sign for the Oysterville cemetery, on Cemetery Road|alt= ]]\n[[File:Grave of Chief Nahcati.jpg|thumb|Chief Nahacati's grave in the Oysterville cemetery| alt=]]\n[[File:Grave for unknown sailors.jpg|thumb|Grave marker for two unknown sailors buried in the Oysterville Cemetery| alt=]]\nThe '''Oysterville cemetery''', one of the oldest cemeteries in Washington State, began in 1858 on land owned by F.C. Davis.<ref name= Images>{{citation| first=Sydney|last=Stevens|title=Images of America: Oysterville|year=2010|page=40|publisher=Arcadia Publishing}}</ref> Located about a quarter of a mile outside the historic gold-rush boom town of [[Oysterville, Washington|Oysterville]], this 2-acre cemetery holds plots for many of the founding families of the area. The history hidden in the headstones of this historic cemetery tell the tale of the Native Americans that lived in the Shoalwater bay region, the first pioneers that came, drawn by the oyster industry, their descendants, and countless lives lost in the treacherous mouth of the Columbia, the [[Graveyard of the Pacific]]. A memorial to the last Native American chieftain of the Long Beach peninsula sits just to the right of the entrance, and a wooden sign with a marble headstone honors the unknown sailors lost at sea with the beginning of Revelations 20:13, \"And the sea gave up the dead\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitlongbeachpeninsula.com/oysterville-walking-tour/|title=Oysterville Walking Tour|access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe original acre territory of the Oysterville cemetery was originally purchased from F.C. Davis in 1890 for $100 by the Oysterville Cemetery Association. However, the land had been used as the town's burial ground for over 30 years at that point.<ref name = Oysterville>{{citation| first= Marie|last=Oesting|title= Oysterville Cemetery Sketches| year=1988| publisher= Cole}}</ref> This territory was later expanded in 1979 by a half-acre donation from the Espy family, and now houses the new section of the cemetery.<ref name= Oysterville />\nThe cemetery holds many descendants of the two founders of Oysterville, the Espy and Clark family, as well as members of many of the early settler families of the area. <ref>{{cite| title= Oysterville Cemetery map| publisher=Tucker Wachsmuth}}</ref>\nThe earliest death date in the cemetery is 1951, three years before the town of Oysterville was founded. This grave belongs to John Carruthers, who was not originally buried in the cemetery, but transferred there by his brother Roberts so he could be buried with his father, mother, and brother.<ref name= Oysterville /> \nThe cemetery is located near a Native American burial ground, and though there is a grave for Chief Nahcati of the Chinook, located in the northwest corner of the cemetery, it is thought that he is actually buried farther west on Bud Goulter's farm.<ref name= Oysterville /> There is also record of the last Native American princess of the area, Myrtle Jane Johnson Woodcock, being buried in plot 67.<ref>{{cite web|first=T|last=Sheldon|title=Oysterville Cemetery; Pacific County, Washington|year=2003|url=http://www.interment.net/data/us/wa/pacific/oysterville/index.htm|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> She was the great granddaughter of chief Uhlahnee of the Chinook band at Celilo Falls, and great granddaughter of Chief Hoqueem of the Quinault tribe.<ref name= Oysterville />\nThere is also a grave for John Douglas, the first American settler on Shoalwater bay, but it is uncertain if he is actually buried there.<ref name = Images/> The current graves of both John Douglas and Chief Nahcati were built by Boy Scout troop number 44 under the direction of Herman Eberhardt, whose grave is built in a matching style.<ref name= Oysterville />\n\n==Management==\nThe Oysterville Cemetery has been managed by the Oysterville Cemetery Association since 1890. The current Oysterville Cemetery Association Board of Trustees is comprised of Chester (Tucker) Wachsmuth, president; Charles Wachsmuth, vice president; Charlie Talbott, secretary/treasurer; and Gordon Andrews, trustee.<ref>{{cite| first = Tucker| last= Wachsmuth| title= Oysterville Cemetery Board| year = 2019}}</ref> The transfer of power to the current management occured on January 15, 2017. Past president Ron Biggs transferred responsibilities to the current president Tucker Wachsmuth, and secretary Sydney Stevens transferred responsibilities to Kitt Fleming.<ref>{{cite web| first= Sidney|last= Stevens| date= 15 January 2017| title= The Changing of the Guard| url= http://sydneyofoysterville.com/category/oysterville-cemetery/| access-date= 21 February 2020}}</ref> The cemetery association works to maintain the cemetery and keep records of burials, deeds, and plot information. General maintenance is often done on a volunteer basis, however, the volunteers are usually members of the board of trustees. <ref>{{cite web| first= Sidney| last= Stevens| date= 25 March 2016| title= Division of Labor| url= http://sydneyofoysterville.com/category/oysterville-cemetery/| access-date= 19 April 2020}}</ref>\nInterments at the Oysterville Cemetery are handled by Penttila's Chapel by the Sea with payments directly to the Oysterville Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web| title= Regarding burial of cremated remains in Peninsula Cemeteries| publisher = Penttilaschapel| url= http://www.meaningfulfunerals.net/fh_live/15900/15924/media/inurnment_1.pdf| access-date = 22 February 2020}}</ref> The funeral home handles burials and tombstone placement, and the Cemetery Association marks the placements.<ref name = Tucker/> The Cemetery accepts both full body and cremated remains.<ref name = Tucker>{{cite| first = Tucker| last= Wachsmuth| title= Email correspondence with author| date = 17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cemetery map==\nThe original linen map of the Cemetery measures 2' wide by 8' long, but current president Tucker Wachsmuth \"scanned the old map, cleaned it up, added the names in print form, cut it up into the nine sections and added the key.<ref>{{cite| first = Tucker| last= Wachsmuth| title= Email correspondence with author| date = 13 February 2020}}</ref>\"\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map.jpg|thumb|All nine sections of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 1.jpg|thumb|First section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 2.jpg|thumb|Second section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 3.jpg|thumb|Third section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 4.jpg|thumb|Fourth section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 5.jpg|thumb|Fifth section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 6.jpg|thumb|Sixth section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 7.jpg|thumb|Seventh section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 8.jpg|thumb|Eighth section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 9.jpg|thumb|Ninth section of the cemetery map\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|46.5476|-124.0335|type:landmark_region:US-WA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1858 establishments in Washington Territory]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Pacific County, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n[[File:Oysterville cemetery sign.jpg|thumb|Wooden sign for the Oysterville cemetery, on Cemetery Road|alt= ]]\n[[File:Grave of Chief Nahcati.jpg|thumb|Chief Nahacati's grave in the Oysterville cemetery| alt=]]\n[[File:Grave for unknown sailors.jpg|thumb|Grave marker for two unknown sailors buried in the Oysterville Cemetery| alt=]]\nThe '''Oysterville cemetery''', one of the oldest cemeteries in Washington State, began in 1858 on land owned by F.C. Davis.<ref name= Images>{{citation| first=Sydney|last=Stevens|title=Images of America: Oysterville|year=2010|page=40|publisher=Arcadia Publishing}}</ref> Located about a quarter of a mile outside the historic gold-rush boom town of [[Oysterville, Washington|Oysterville]], this 2-acre cemetery holds plots for many of the founding families of the area. The history hidden in the headstones of this historic cemetery tell the tale of the Native Americans that lived in the Shoalwater bay region, the first pioneers that came, drawn by the oyster industry, their descendants, and countless lives lost in the treacherous mouth of the Columbia, the [[Graveyard of the Pacific]]. A memorial to the last Native American chieftain of the Long Beach peninsula sits just to the right of the entrance, and a wooden sign with a marble headstone honors the unknown sailors lost at sea with the beginning of Revelations 20:13, \"And the sea gave up the dead\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitlongbeachpeninsula.com/oysterville-walking-tour/|title=Oysterville Walking Tour|access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe original acre territory of the Oysterville cemetery was originally purchased from F.C. Davis in 1890 for $100 by the Oysterville Cemetery Association. However, the land had been used as the town's burial ground for over 30 years at that point.<ref name = Oysterville>{{citation| first= Marie|last=Oesting|title= Oysterville Cemetery Sketches| year=1988| publisher= Cole}}</ref> This territory was later expanded in 1979 by a half-acre donation from the Espy family, and now houses the new section of the cemetery.<ref name= Oysterville />\nThe cemetery holds many descendants of the two founders of Oysterville, the Espy and Clark family, as well as members of many of the early settler families of the area. <ref>{{cite| title= Oysterville Cemetery map| publisher=Tucker Wachsmuth}}</ref>\nThe earliest death date in the cemetery is 1951, three years before the town of Oysterville was founded. This grave belongs to John Carruthers, who was not originally buried in the cemetery, but transferred there by his brother Roberts so he could be buried with his father, mother, and brother.<ref name= Oysterville /> \nThe cemetery is located near a Native American burial ground, and though there is a grave for Chief Nahcati of the Chinook, located in the northwest corner of the cemetery, it is thought that he is actually buried farther west on Bud Goulter's farm.<ref name= Oysterville /> There is also record of the last Native American princess of the area, Myrtle Jane Johnson Woodcock, being buried in plot 67.<ref>{{cite web|first=T|last=Sheldon|title=Oysterville Cemetery; Pacific County, Washington|year=2003|url=http://www.interment.net/data/us/wa/pacific/oysterville/index.htm|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> She was the great granddaughter of chief Uhlahnee of the Chinook band at Celilo Falls, and great granddaughter of Chief Hoqueem of the Quinault tribe.<ref name= Oysterville />\nThere is also a grave for John Douglas, the first American settler on Shoalwater bay, but it is uncertain if he is actually buried there.<ref name = Images/> The current graves of both John Douglas and Chief Nahcati were built by Boy Scout troop number 44 under the direction of Herman Eberhardt, whose grave is built in a matching style.<ref name= Oysterville />\n\n==Management==\nThe Oysterville Cemetery has been managed by the Oysterville Cemetery Association since 1890. The current Oysterville Cemetery Association Board of Trustees is comprised of Chester (Tucker) Wachsmuth, president; Charles Wachsmuth, vice president; Charlie Talbott, secretary/treasurer; and Gordon Andrews, trustee.<ref>{{cite| first = Tucker| last= Wachsmuth| title= Oysterville Cemetery Board| year = 2019}}</ref> The transfer of power to the current management occured on January 15, 2017. Past president Ron Biggs transferred responsibilities to the current president Tucker Wachsmuth, and secretary Sydney Stevens transferred responsibilities to Kitt Fleming.<ref>{{cite web| first= Sidney|last= Stevens| date= 15 January 2017| title= The Changing of the Guard| url= http://sydneyofoysterville.com/category/oysterville-cemetery/| access-date= 21 February 2020}}</ref> The cemetery association works to maintain the cemetery and keep records of burials, deeds, and plot information. General maintenance is often done on a volunteer basis, however, the volunteers are usually members of the board of trustees. <ref>{{cite web| first= Sidney| last= Stevens| date= 25 March 2016| title= Division of Labor| url= http://sydneyofoysterville.com/category/oysterville-cemetery/| access-date= 19 April 2020}}</ref>\nInterments at the Oysterville Cemetery are handled by Penttila's Chapel by the Sea with payments directly to the Oysterville Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web| title= Regarding burial of cremated remains in Peninsula Cemeteries| publisher = Penttilaschapel| url= http://www.meaningfulfunerals.net/fh_live/15900/15924/media/inurnment_1.pdf| access-date = 22 February 2020}}</ref> The funeral home handles burials and tombstone placement, and the Cemetery Association marks the placements.<ref name = Tucker/> The Cemetery accepts both full body and cremated remains.<ref name = Tucker>{{cite| first = Tucker| last= Wachsmuth| title= Email correspondence with author| date = 17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cemetery Map==\nThe original linen map of the Cemetery measures 2' wide by 8' long, but current president Tucker Wachsmuth \"scanned the old map, cleaned it up, added the names in print form, cut it up into the nine sections and added the key.<ref>{{cite| first = Tucker| last= Wachsmuth| title= Email correspondence with author| date = 13 February 2020}}</ref>\"\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map.jpg|thumb|All nine sections of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 1.jpg|thumb|First section of the cemetery map\nFile:Oysterville Cemetery Map Section 2.jpg|thumb|Second section of the cemetery map\nFi