e ever seen.\n|LineColor       = 301934\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 17\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n|Title           = A Nutty Halloween!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|04}}\n|ShortSummary    = Chip and Dale carve a giant jack-o'-lantern for a Halloween contest at Clarabelle's Barn.\n|LineColor       = 301934\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 18\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n|Title           = Tinsel Tussle!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|30}}\n|ShortSummary    = Chip and Dale have found the perfect Christmas tree, but before they can take it home, they must face a dancing groundhog who wants the tree for himself.\n|LineColor       = 301934\n}}\n}}\n\n===Mickey Mouse: Hot Diggity-Dog Tales===\n{{Episode table\n|background = #FFD700\n|overall    = 11\n|title      = 65\n|titleR     = <ref>{{cite web|url= https://tvschedule.zap2it.com/overview.html?programSeriesId=SH03308141&tmsId=SH033081410000&from=undefined&aid=gapzap|title=Mickey's Mouse Hot Diggity-Dog Adventures|publisher=Zap2it|accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|airdate    = 14\n|country    = U.S.\n|episodes   = \n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 1\n|Title           = Mickey's Tricky Tractor!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|14}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 2\n|Title           = Pluto's Howl-A-Ween!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|15}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 3\n|Title           = Catch That Weasel!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|16}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 4\n|Title           = Surf's Up, Mickey!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|17}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 5\n|Title           = Flamingo-A-Go-Go!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|5}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 6\n|Title           = Mickey's Breakfast Blast!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|15}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 7\n|Title           = Goodnight Mickey\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|22}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 8\n|Title           = The Lights Before Christmas!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|30}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 9\n|Title           = Mickey's Hot Dog Dance Party!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|3}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 10\n|Title           = Mickey's Water Hose Woes!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|2}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 11\n|Title           = Dust Bunny Dust-Up!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|3}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 12\n|Title           = Bow-Wow Bath Time!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|4}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 13\n|Title           = Mickey's Choo-Choo Trouble!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 14\n|Title           = Mickey's Carnival Caper!\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|6}}\n|ShortSummary    = \n|LineColor       = FFD700\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{TV series and movies set in the Mickey Mouse universe}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mickey and the Roadster Racers episodes, List of}}\n[[Category:Lists of American children's animated television series episodes]]\n", "name_user": "2001:e68:5433:1697:79a1:489c:c6c5:3f75", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Mickey_Mouse_Mixed-Up_Adventures_episodes"}
{"title_page": "Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta", "text_new": "{{short description|Mountain range in northern Colombia}}\n{{Infobox mountain range\n|name                   = Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n|photo                  = Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta desde el espacio.jpg\n|country                = [[Colombia]]\n|highest                = Pico Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar\n|elevation_m            = 5528\n|coordinates            = {{coord|10|52|00|N|73|43|12|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|length_km              = 1928\n|width_km               = 1100\n|area_km2               = 20\n|length_orientation     = 29\n|width_orientation      = 29\n|map                    = Colombia\n}}\n\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = PNN Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n| alt_name = Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta National Natural Park\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Sierra nevada.JPG\n| photo_caption = Sierra Nevada viewed from [[Valledupar]]\n| nearest_city = [[Santa Marta]], {{flag|Colombia}}\n| area_km2 = 3830\n| established = 1964\n| governing_body = [[National System of Protected Areas (Colombia)|SINAP]]\n| world_heritage_site =\n}}\n\nThe '''Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta''' is an isolated mountain range in northern [[Colombia]], separate from the [[Andes]] range that runs through the centre of the country. Reaching an altitude of {{convert|5700|m|ft|abbr=on}} just {{convert|42|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the Caribbean coast, the Sierra Nevada is one of the world's highest coastal ranges, being 250m shorter than the [[Saint Elias Mountains]] in Canada. The Sierra Nevada encompasses about {{convert|17000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and serves as the source of 36 rivers. The range is in the Departments of [[Magdalena Department|Magdalena]], [[Cesar Department|Cesar]] and [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]].\n\nThe highest point of the Sierra Nevada group (and Colombia in general) may be either [[Pico Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n]] or Pico Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar both in the municipalities of Santa Marta and [[Aracataca]]; it has yet to be determined which is higher. [[SRTM]] data and local topographic maps show that their true elevations are approximately {{convert|5700|m|ft|abbr=on}}, lower than the {{convert|5775|m|ft|abbr=on}} elevation that is often quoted.\n\nThe Sierra Nevada is a compact group, relatively small in area, and completely surrounded by lands with elevations below {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Although it is associated with the [[Tropical Andes]],{{cn}} the main backbone of the Andes cannot be reached from the Sierra Nevada without dropping below this level. This makes its highest point the world's fifth most [[topographic prominence|prominent]] summit.\n\nSeveral peaks in the Sierra Nevada are intervisible with [[Paramillo Massif|Cerro Paramillo]], a {{convert|3730|m|ft|abbr=on}} peak <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=8351|title=Cerro Paramillo - Peakbagger.com|author=|date=|website=www.peakbagger.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> in [[Antioquia Department]]. This implies a theoretical direct line of sight of just over {{convert|500|km|mi|abbr=on}}, reported to be the longest between any two points on the surface of the Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas.html#longlines|title=Panoramas|author=|date=|website=www.viewfinderpanoramas.org|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n\nIt is calculated that the yearly average rainfall is {{convert|4000|mm|in|abbr=on}} at elevations of {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|1500|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Villegas381\">{{harvnb|Villegas|Sesana|2007| p=381}}</ref> The temperature varies between 0&nbsp;\u00b0C and 27&nbsp;\u00b0C.(32-81&nbsp;\u00b0F)<ref name=\"Parque Nacional\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.020224\n |title       = Parque Nacional Natural Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722114338/http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.020224\n |archivedate = 2011-07-22\n}}</ref>\n\n==Biodiversity==\n\nThe tropical rainforest is made up of perennial trees, with a canopy reaching between {{convert|30|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|40|m|ft|abbr=on}}. There is a great variety and large populations of [[epiphyte]]s and [[liana]]s,<ref name=\"Villegas381\"/> and more than 3,000 species of [[vascular plant]]s are found in the area.<ref name=\"Nature\">{{Cite web\n| url         = http://www.nature.org/wherewework/southamerica/colombia/work/art5303.html\n| title       = Colombia: places we protect, Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n}}</ref> The indigenous peoples made an alcoholic beverage from fruits of the palm ''[[Attalea maripa]]'' found at the lower elevations.<ref name=\"Villegas381\"/>\n\nOf Colombia's 340 endemic species, 44 are found in the park, for example seven species of endemic hummingbirds. Of the 3,057 endangered species, 44 are found here.<ref name=\"Science\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=02.012503\n |title       = Nature and Science\n |publisher   = Parques Nacionales Naturales de Colombia\n |accessdate  = 11 July 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722114355/http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=02.012503\n |archivedate = 22 July 2011\n}}</ref> The area is home to 440 species of birds,<ref name=\"Villegas381\"/> including [[black-fronted wood-quail]], [[king vulture]], [[Andean condor]], [[Santa Marta warbler]] and [[Santa Marta parakeet]].<ref name=\"Science\" /> Mammals found in the park include: [[tapir]], [[cougar]], [[jaguar]], [[squirrel]], ''[[Transandinomys talamancae]]'', [[otter]], and [[brocket deer]].<ref name=\"Science\" />\n\nThe Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta is home to a number of [[ecoregion]]s, which vary with elevation.\n\nThe [[Guajira-Barranquilla xeric scrub]] region lies near the Caribbean seacoast to the north of the range. The [[Sin\u00fa Valley dry forests]] cover the range's lower slopes, up to an elevation of {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe [[Santa Marta montane forests]] lie above {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The montane forests are separated from other moist forests by the lower-elevation dry forests and xeric shrublands, and have large numbers of [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species. The montane forest ecoregion has several distinct plant communities, distinguished by altitude and rainfall; moist lowland forests cover the windward northern and western flanks of the range between {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and the drier eastern and southern flanks from {{convert|5800|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Above {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}} is a transitional forest zone of smaller trees and palms. [[Cloud forest]]s occur above {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}}; the Sub-Andean forests from {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|2500|m|ft|abbr=on}} form a canopy {{convert|25|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|35|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall, while the higher-elevation Andean forests, between {{convert|2500|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|3300|m|ft|abbr=on}}, grow to {{convert|15|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|20|m|ft|abbr=on}} in height.\n\nThe [[Santa Marta P\u00e1ramo]], a high altitude belt of [[montane grasslands and shrublands]] interspersed with marshes and acid bogs, occupies the zone between {{convert|3300|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The Santa Marta P\u00e1ramo is the northernmost enclave of [[P\u00e1ramo]] in South America, which occur along the Andes belt. Above {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}} meters lies the permanent snow cap.\n\n==National Natural Park==\n\nThe '''Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta National Natural Park''' ({{lang-es|Parque Nacional Natural Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta}}) is [[Colombia]]'s second oldest [[national park]], established in 1964.<ref name=\"IUCN127\">{{harvnb|IUCN|1982|p=127}}</ref> It is located in the [[Cordillera Oriental (Colombia)|Cordillera Oriental range]], between the departments of [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]], [[Magdalena Department|Magdalena]] and [[Cesar Department|Cesar]], in the mountain range of the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta. It is a sanctuary as well as a tourist attraction, because it offers different climate, terrain, flora and fauna environments, ranging from [[beach]]es to snowy mountain peaks. Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta National Natural Park is considered a unique place in the world due to its isolation from the Andes and its highest peak (5700 meters above sea level) is located just 42&nbsp;km away from the sea.\n\n<!-- It belongs geographically to the [[Amazon Basin]], but it is [[Hydrography|hydrographically]] a part of the [[Orinoco|Orinoco River]] basin. <ref name=\"Villegas381\"/> -->All the water courses that originate in the national park drain to the Caribbean sea whether directly (e. g. rivers Rancher\u00eda, Don Diego, Palomino, Buritaca, Guachaca, Ca\u00f1as, etc.) or through the [[Magdalena River]] system that includes the [[Ci\u00e9naga Grande de Santa Marta]], (e. g., rivers [[Cesar River|Cesar]], Ariguan\u00ed, Fundaci\u00f3n, Fr\u00edo, Aracataca, etc.). Roughly 1.2 million people are dependent upon the freshwater supplied by the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta rivers.<ref name=\"Nature\" /><ref name=\"IUCN127\" /> There are currently about 30,000 [[indigenous peoples|indigenous people]] of the ethnic groups [[Koguis]], [[Arhuacos]], [[Kankuamos]] and [[Wiwa people|Wiwa]] living in the area.<ref name=\"Parque Nacional\" /> This park is also home to the remnants of the [[Tairona|Tairona Culture]]. In 1979 the park was designated a [[Man and the Biosphere Programme|Biosphere reserve]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref name=\"Parque Nacional\" /><ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{Cite web\n| url         = http://www.unesco.org/mabdb/br/brdir/directory/biores.asp?code=COL+03&mode=all\n| title       = Biosphere Reserve Information, Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n| publisher   = [[UNESCO]]\n| accessdate  = 11 July 2010\n}}</ref>\nA 2013 report by the International Union for Conservation of Nature on the world's most irreplaceable protected areas identified the park as the most irreplaceable park in the world for threatened species.<ref name=\"IUCN\">{{Cite web\n| url         = http://www.iucn.org/?14008/Scientists-identify-the-worlds-most-irreplaceable-protected-areas\n| title       = Scientists identify the world\u2019s most irreplaceable protected areas\n| publisher   = [[IUCN]]\n| accessdate  = 21 November 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\n\nIt is composed of Cretaceous metamorphic rocks (predominantly schists and gneisses) and quartzdioritic intrusives of Tertiary age. The Quaternary of the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta is mainly represented by colluvial-alluvial valley fill and by recent beach deposits. The coastlines of the northwestern part of the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta are indented, reflecting the alternation of rocky headlands and deep, NNW trending tectonically controlled bays. The headlands are typically {{convert|100|to|150|m|ft|abbr=on}} high plunging cliffs cut into schists and granites, whereas the embayments front alluvial valley deposits. The bay shores are typically steep, reflective beaches composed of very coarse sand to granules eroded from adjacent cliffs and alluvial deposits. Wide pocket beaches and tombolos are common along sectors with abundant rocky erosional remnants and stacks.<ref name=USGS>{{cite web| url= http://coastal.er.usgs.gov/coasts-colombia/caribbean/sierra-nevada.html |publisher= US Geological Survey |title= Caribbean Coast: Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta Coast| accessdate= 24 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Inhabitants ==\n\nThe Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta is home to the remnants of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[Tairona|Tairona Culture]]; [[Arhuacos]], [[Koguis]], [[Wiwas]] and [[Kankuamos]], that live in ''Resguardos Indigenas'' (Indian reserves) located in the mid-highlands. <!--links can be found in articles-->\n\n===Recent access problems===\n\nFor the last ten years, access to the highest summits has been very difficult, and this situation continues, [http://www.summitpost.org/sierra-nevada-de-santa-marta/317419] although there is a documented ascent of [[Pico Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n]] in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ii.uib.no/~petter/mountains/5000mtn/Cristobal/Trip-report.html |title=Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta Trip Report, December 3rd. 2015 - December 16th. 2015 |work=Mountains I have climbed and remember |first=Petter |last=Bj\u00f8rstad |accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The only safe and relatively straight forward access is from Santa Marta city to Cuchillo de San Lorenzo, but that is only to {{convert|2800|m|ft|abbr=on}} (although it provides excellent views of the peaks).\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ciudad Perdida]]\n* [[Tayrona]]\n* [[Juan Mayr]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}} \n* http://www.colombia.com/colombiainfo/parquesnaturales/sierranevada.asp\n*{{Citation |last=IUCN |first= |authorlink=International Union for Conservation of Nature |year=1982 |title=IUCN directory of neotropical protected areas |publisher=IUCN |isbn=978-0-907567-62-2|postscript=.|language=Spanish, English|url=https://archive.org/details/iucndirectoryofn82iucn}}\n*{{Citation|last=Villegas|first=Benjamin|last2=Sesana|first2=Laura|year=2007 |title=Colombia Natural Parks|publisher=Villegas Asociados |isbn=978-958-8156-87-3|postscript=.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HoDPr04hHCQC}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Santa Marta montane forests|id=nt0159}}\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Santa Marta P\u00e1ramo|id=nt1007}}\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Sin\u00fa Valley dry forests|id=nt0229}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110417010431/http://www.aaas.org/international/ehn/biod/maldon.htm Case study by Fundaci\u00f3n Pr\u00f3-Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2009/oct/24/colombia-lost-city-kidnapping?page=all The Guardian].com: \"The Lure of Colombia's Lost City\" (2009)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140714172521/http://www.hiddenjourneys.co.uk/Audio%20Slideshows.aspx#level_11 Royal Geography Society \u2212 Hidden Journeys project: \"Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta \u2212 Sampling the food cultures of northern Colombia with hungry cyclist Tom Kevill-Davies\"] \u2014 ''audio slideshow''.\n\n{{Mountain Ranges of Colombia}}\n{{Protected areas of Colombia}}\n{{Treasures of Colombia}}\n\n[[Category:Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta| 01]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Colombia|Santa Marta]]\n[[Category:Tropical Andes]]\n[[Category:National parks of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cesar Department]]\n[[Category:Geography of La Guajira Department]]\n[[Category:Geography of Magdalena Department]]\n[[Category:Glaciers of Colombia|Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta]]\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Colombia]]\n[[Category:P\u00e1ramos]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cesar Department]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in La Guajira Department]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Magdalena Department]]\n[[Category:Magdalena River]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List for Colombia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mountain range in northern Colombia}}\n{{Infobox mountain range\n|name                   = Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n|photo                  = Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta desde el espacio.jpg\n|country                = [[Colombia]]\n|highest                = Pico Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar\n|elevation_m            = 5528\n|coordinates            = {{coord|10|52|00|N|73|43|12|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|length_km              = 1928\n|width_km               = 1100\n|area_km2               = 20\n|length_orientation     = 29\n|width_orientation      = 29\n|map                    = Colombia\n}}\n\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = PNN Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n| alt_name = Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta National Natural Park\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Sierra nevada.JPG\n| photo_caption = Sierra Nevada viewed from [[Valledupar]]\n| nearest_city = [[Santa Marta]], {{flag|Colombia}}\n| area_km2 = 3830\n| established = 1964\n| governing_body = [[National System of Protected Areas (Colombia)|SINAP]]\n| world_heritage_site =\n}}\n\nThe '''Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta''' is an isolated mountain range in northern [[Colombia]], separate from the [[Andes]] range that runs through the centre of the country. Reaching an altitude of {{convert|5700|m|ft|abbr=on}} just {{convert|42|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the Caribbean coast, the Sierra Nevada is one of the world's highest coastal ranges, being 250m shorter than the [[Saint Elias Mountains]] in Canada. The Sierra Nevada encompasses about {{convert|17000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and serves as the source of 36 rivers. The range is in the Departments of [[Magdalena Department|Magdalena]], [[Cesar Department|Cesar]] and [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]].\n\nThe highest point of the Sierra Nevada group (and Colombia in general) may be either [[Pico Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n]] or Pico Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar both in the municipalities of Santa Marta and [[Aracataca]]; it has yet to be determined which is higher. [[SRTM]] data and local topographic maps show that their true elevations are approximately {{convert|5700|m|ft|abbr=on}}, lower than the {{convert|5775|m|ft|abbr=on}} elevation that is often quoted.\n\nThe Sierra Nevada is a compact group, relatively small in area, and completely surrounded by lands with elevations below {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Although it is associated with the [[Tropical Andes]],{{citerequired}} the main backbone of the Andes cannot be reached from the Sierra Nevada without dropping below this level. This makes its highest point the world's fifth most [[topographic prominence|prominent]] summit.\n\nSeveral peaks in the Sierra Nevada are intervisible with [[Paramillo Massif|Cerro Paramillo]], a {{convert|3730|m|ft|abbr=on}} peak <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=8351|title=Cerro Paramillo - Peakbagger.com|author=|date=|website=www.peakbagger.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> in [[Antioquia Department]]. This implies a theoretical direct line of sight of just over {{convert|500|km|mi|abbr=on}}, reported to be the longest between any two points on the surface of the Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas.html#longlines|title=Panoramas|author=|date=|website=www.viewfinderpanoramas.org|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n\nIt is calculated that the yearly average rainfall is {{convert|4000|mm|in|abbr=on}} at elevations of {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|1500|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Villegas381\">{{harvnb|Villegas|Sesana|2007| p=381}}</ref> The temperature varies between 0&nbsp;\u00b0C and 27&nbsp;\u00b0C.(32-81&nbsp;\u00b0F)<ref name=\"Parque Nacional\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.020224\n |title       = Parque Nacional Natural Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722114338/http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=01.020224\n |archivedate = 2011-07-22\n}}</ref>\n\n==Biodiversity==\n\nThe tropical rainforest is made up of perennial trees, with a canopy reaching between {{convert|30|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|40|m|ft|abbr=on}}. There is a great variety and large populations of [[epiphyte]]s and [[liana]]s,<ref name=\"Villegas381\"/> and more than 3,000 species of [[vascular plant]]s are found in the area.<ref name=\"Nature\">{{Cite web\n| url         = http://www.nature.org/wherewework/southamerica/colombia/work/art5303.html\n| title       = Colombia: places we protect, Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n}}</ref> The indigenous peoples made an alcoholic beverage from fruits of the palm ''[[Attalea maripa]]'' found at the lower elevations.<ref name=\"Villegas381\"/>\n\nOf Colombia's 340 endemic species, 44 are found in the park, for example seven species of endemic hummingbirds. Of the 3,057 endangered species, 44 are found here.<ref name=\"Science\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=02.012503\n |title       = Nature and Science\n |publisher   = Parques Nacionales Naturales de Colombia\n |accessdate  = 11 July 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722114355/http://www.parquesnacionales.gov.co/PNN/portel/libreria/php/decide.php?patron=02.012503\n |archivedate = 22 July 2011\n}}</ref> The area is home to 440 species of birds,<ref name=\"Villegas381\"/> including [[black-fronted wood-quail]], [[king vulture]], [[Andean condor]], [[Santa Marta warbler]] and [[Santa Marta parakeet]].<ref name=\"Science\" /> Mammals found in the park include: [[tapir]], [[cougar]], [[jaguar]], [[squirrel]], ''[[Transandinomys talamancae]]'', [[otter]], and [[brocket deer]].<ref name=\"Science\" />\n\nThe Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta is home to a number of [[ecoregion]]s, which vary with elevation.\n\nThe [[Guajira-Barranquilla xeric scrub]] region lies near the Caribbean seacoast to the north of the range. The [[Sin\u00fa Valley dry forests]] cover the range's lower slopes, up to an elevation of {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe [[Santa Marta montane forests]] lie above {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|800|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The montane forests are separated from other moist forests by the lower-elevation dry forests and xeric shrublands, and have large numbers of [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] species. The montane forest ecoregion has several distinct plant communities, distinguished by altitude and rainfall; moist lowland forests cover the windward northern and western flanks of the range between {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and the drier eastern and southern flanks from {{convert|5800|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Above {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}} is a transitional forest zone of smaller trees and palms. [[Cloud forest]]s occur above {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}}; the Sub-Andean forests from {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|2500|m|ft|abbr=on}} form a canopy {{convert|25|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|35|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall, while the higher-elevation Andean forests, between {{convert|2500|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|3300|m|ft|abbr=on}}, grow to {{convert|15|m|ft|abbr=on}} to {{convert|20|m|ft|abbr=on}} in height.\n\nThe [[Santa Marta P\u00e1ramo]], a high altitude belt of [[montane grasslands and shrublands]] interspersed with marshes and acid bogs, occupies the zone between {{convert|3300|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The Santa Marta P\u00e1ramo is the northernmost enclave of [[P\u00e1ramo]] in South America, which occur along the Andes belt. Above {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}} meters lies the permanent snow cap.\n\n==National Natural Park==\n\nThe '''Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta National Natural Park''' ({{lang-es|Parque Nacional Natural Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta}}) is [[Colombia]]'s second oldest [[national park]], established in 1964.<ref name=\"IUCN127\">{{harvnb|IUCN|1982|p=127}}</ref> It is located in the [[Cordillera Oriental (Colombia)|Cordillera Oriental range]], between the departments of [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]], [[Magdalena Department|Magdalena]] and [[Cesar Department|Cesar]], in the mountain range of the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta. It is a sanctuary as well as a tourist attraction, because it offers different climate, terrain, flora and fauna environments, ranging from [[beach]]es to snowy mountain peaks. Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta National Natural Park is considered a unique place in the world due to its isolation from the Andes and its highest peak (5700 meters above sea level) is located just 42&nbsp;km away from the sea.\n\n<!-- It belongs geographically to the [[Amazon Basin]], but it is [[Hydrography|hydrographically]] a part of the [[Orinoco|Orinoco River]] basin. <ref name=\"Villegas381\"/> -->All the water courses that originate in the national park drain to the Caribbean sea whether directly (e. g. rivers Rancher\u00eda, Don Diego, Palomino, Buritaca, Guachaca, Ca\u00f1as, etc.) or through the [[Magdalena River]] system that includes the [[Ci\u00e9naga Grande de Santa Marta]], (e. g., rivers [[Cesar River|Cesar]], Ariguan\u00ed, Fundaci\u00f3n, Fr\u00edo, Aracataca, etc.). Roughly 1.2 million people are dependent upon the freshwater supplied by the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta rivers.<ref name=\"Nature\" /><ref name=\"IUCN127\" /> There are currently about 30,000 [[indigenous peoples|indigenous people]] of the ethnic groups [[Koguis]], [[Arhuacos]], [[Kankuamos]] and [[Wiwa people|Wiwa]] living in the area.<ref name=\"Parque Nacional\" /> This park is also home to the remnants of the [[Tairona|Tairona Culture]]. In 1979 the park was designated a [[Man and the Biosphere Programme|Biosphere reserve]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref name=\"Parque Nacional\" /><ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{Cite web\n| url         = http://www.unesco.org/mabdb/br/brdir/directory/biores.asp?code=COL+03&mode=all\n| title       = Biosphere Reserve Information, Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta\n| publisher   = [[UNESCO]]\n| accessdate  = 11 July 2010\n}}</ref>\nA 2013 report by the International Union for Conservation of Nature on the world's most irreplaceable protected areas identified the park as the most irreplaceable park in the world for threatened species.<ref name=\"IUCN\">{{Cite web\n| url         = http://www.iucn.org/?14008/Scientists-identify-the-worlds-most-irreplaceable-protected-areas\n| title       = Scientists identify the world\u2019s most irreplaceable protected areas\n| publisher   = [[IUCN]]\n| accessdate  = 21 November 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\n\nIt is composed of Cretaceous metamorphic rocks (predominantly schists and gneisses) and quartzdioritic intrusives of Tertiary age. The Quaternary of the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta is mainly represented by colluvial-alluvial valley fill and by recent beach deposits. The coastlines of the northwestern part of the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta are indented, reflecting the alternation of rocky headlands and deep, NNW trending tectonically controlled bays. The headlands are typically {{convert|100|to|150|m|ft|abbr=on}} high plunging cliffs cut into schists and granites, whereas the embayments front alluvial valley deposits. The bay shores are typically steep, reflective beaches composed of very coarse sand to granules eroded from adjacent cliffs and alluvial deposits. Wide pocket beaches and tombolos are common along sectors with abundant rocky erosional remnants and stacks.<ref name=USGS>{{cite web| url= http://coastal.er.usgs.gov/coasts-colombia/caribbean/sierra-nevada.html |publisher= US Geological Survey |title= Caribbean Coast: Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta Coast| accessdate= 24 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Inhabitants ==\n\nThe Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta is home to the remnants of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[Tairona|Tairona Culture]]; [[Arhuacos]], [[Koguis]], [[Wiwas]] and [[Kankuamos]], that live in ''Resguardos Indigenas'' (Indian reserves) located in the mid-highlands. <!--links can be found in articles-->\n\n===Recent access problems===\n\nFor the last ten years, access to the highest summits has been very difficult, and this situation continues, [http://www.summitpost.org/sierra-nevada-de-santa-marta/317419] although there is a documented ascent of [[Pico Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n]] in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ii.uib.no/~petter/mountains/5000mtn/Cristobal/Trip-report.html |title=Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta Trip Report, December 3rd. 2015 - December 16th. 2015 |work=Mountains I have climbed and remember |first=Petter |last=Bj\u00f8rstad |accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The only safe and relatively straight forward access is from Santa Marta city to Cuchillo de San Lorenzo, but that is only to {{convert|2800|m|ft|abbr=on}} (although it provides excellent views of the peaks).\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ciudad Perdida]]\n* [[Tayrona]]\n* [[Juan Mayr]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}} \n* http://www.colombia.com/colombiainfo/parquesnaturales/sierranevada.asp\n*{{Citation |last=IUCN |first= |authorlink=International Union for Conservation of Nature |year=1982 |title=IUCN directory of neotropical protected areas |publisher=IUCN |isbn=978-0-907567-62-2|postscript=.|language=Spanish, English|url=https://archive.org/details/iucndirectoryofn82iucn}}\n*{{Citation|last=Villegas|first=Benjamin|last2=Sesana|first2=Laura|year=2007 |title=Colombia Natural Parks|publisher=Villegas Asociados |isbn=978-958-8156-87-3|postscript=.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HoDPr04hHCQC}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Santa Marta montane forests|id=nt0159}}\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Santa Marta P\u00e1ramo|id=nt1007}}\n* {{WWF ecoregion|name=Sin\u00fa Valley dry forests|id=nt0229}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110417010431/http://www.aaas.org/international/ehn/biod/maldon.htm Case study by Fundaci\u00f3n Pr\u00f3-Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2009/oct/24/colombia-lost-city-kidnapping?page=all The Guardian].com: \"The Lure of Colombia's Lost City\" (2009)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140714172521/http://www.hiddenjourneys.co.uk/Audio%20Slideshows.aspx#level_11 Royal Geography Society \u2212 Hidden Journeys project: \"Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta \u2212 Sampling the food cultures of northern Colombia with hungry cyclist Tom Kevill-Davies\"] \u2014 ''audio slideshow''.\n\n{{Mountain Ranges of Colombia}}\n{{Protected areas of Colombia}}\n{{Treasures of Colombia}}\n\n[[Category:Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta| 01]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Colombia|Santa Marta]]\n[[Category:Tropical Andes]]\n[[Category:National parks of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cesar Department]]\n[[Category:Geography of La Guajira Department]]\n[[Category:Geography of Magdalena Department]]\n[[Category:Glaciers of Colombia|Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta]]\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Colombia]]\n[[Category:P\u00e1ramos]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cesar Department]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in La Guajira Department]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Magdalena Department]]\n[[Category:Magdalena River]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List for Colombia]]\n", "name_user": "CJK09", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierra_Nevada_de_Santa_Marta"}
{"title_page": "Pacific sleeper shark", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Pacific sleeper shark\n| image = Pacific sleeper shark.png\n| status = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN\">{{Cite iucn | author = Ebert, D.A. | author2 = Goldman, K.J. | author3 = Orlov, A.M. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Somniosus pacificus'' | volume = 2009 | page = e.T161403A5416294 | date = 2009 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2009-2.RLTS.T161403A5416294.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Somniosus\n| species = pacificus\n| range_map = Somniosus pacificus distmap.png\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Pacific sleeper shark\n| authority = [[Henry Bryant Bigelow|Bigelow]] & [[William Charles Schroeder|Schroeder]], 1944\n| synonyms =\n| synonyms_ref =\n}}\n[[File:Somniosus pacificus noaa2.jpg|thumb|Pacific sleeper shark carcasses]]\nThe '''Pacific sleeper shark''' (''Somniosus pacificus'') is a [[sleeper shark]] of the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Somniosidae]], found in the North Pacific on [[continental shelves]] and slopes in [[Arctic]] and [[temperate]] waters between [[latitude]]s [[70th parallel north|70\u00b0N]] and [[22nd parallel north|22\u00b0N]], from the surface to {{convert|2000|m|ft}} deep.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/><ref name=fishbase>{{FishBase | genus = Somniosus | species =  pacificus | month = March| year = 2016}}</ref> Records from southern oceans are likely misidentifications of [[Somniosus|relatives]].<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> Its length is up to {{convert|4.4|m|ft|abbr=on}}, although it could possibly reach lengths in excess of {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=fishbase/>\n\n==Feeding habits==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2015}}\nPacific sleeper sharks, which are thought to be both predators and scavengers, can glide through the water with little body movement and little hydrodynamic noise, making them successful stealth predators. They feed by means of suction and cutting of their prey. They have large mouths that can essentially inhale prey and their teeth cut up any pieces that are too large to swallow. They show a characteristic rolling motion of the head when feeding. Only in [[Alaska]] has the shark's diet been studied - most sharks' stomachs contain remains of [[giant Pacific octopus]]. They are also known to feed on bottom-dwelling [[teleost]] fishes, as well as [[Sole (fish)|soles]], [[flounder]]s, [[Alaska pollock]], [[Sebastes|rockfishes]], [[shrimp]]s, [[hermit crab]]s, and even marine [[snail]]s. Larger Pacific sleeper sharks are also found to feed on fast-swimming prey such as [[squid]]s, [[Pacific salmon]], and [[harbor porpoise]]s. The diet of the Pacific sleeper shark seems to broaden as they increase in size. For example, a 3.7-m female shark found off [[Trinidad, California]] was found to have fed mostly on [[giant squid]]. Sleeper sharks found in Alaskan waters from {{convert|2|to|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} seem to feed mostly on flounder, pollock, and [[cephalopoda|cephalopods]], while sleeper sharks {{convert|3.3|to|4.25|m|ft|abbr=on}} long seem to consume teleosts and cephalopods, as well as [[marine mammal]]s. A recent study in the Gulf of Alaska suggests that sleeper sharks may prey on juvenile Steller sea lions.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Markus Horning|author2=Jo-Ann Mellish|last-author-amp=yes|title=In cold blood: evidence of Pacific sleeper shark (''Somniosus pacificus'') predation on Steller sea lions (''Eumetopias jubatus'') in the Gulf of Alaska|doi=10.7755/FB.112.4.6|year=2014|journal=Fishery Bulletin|volume=112|issue=4|pages=297\u2013310|url=http://ir.library.oregonstate.edu/xmlui/bitstream/1957/54605/1/HorningMarkusFisheriesWildlifeInColdBlood.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\nVery little is known about the early life of Pacific sleeper sharks. They are believed to produce eggs that hatch inside the female's body (reproduction is [[ovoviviparity|ovoviviparous]]), but gestation time is unknown and litter sizes are thought to be about 10 pups. Its length at birth is about {{convert|42|cm|ft|abbr=on}} or less.<ref name=\"RQ\"/>\n\n==Size==\nThe average mature size is {{convert|3.65|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|318|-|363|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. The largest Pacific sleeper shark verified in size measured {{convert|4.4|m|ft|abbr=on}} long and weighed {{convert|888|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, although it could possibly reach {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} or more.<ref name=fishbase/><ref name= Castro>Castro, Jos\u00e9 I., ''The Sharks of North America''. Oxford University Press (2011), {{ISBN|978-0-19-539294-4}}</ref> In 1989, an enormous Pacific sleeper shark was attracted to a bait in deep water outside [[Tokyo Bay]], [[Japan]], and filmed. The shark was estimated by [[Eugenie Clark]] to be about {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"RQ\">{{cite web|author=Martin, R. Aidan|title=Elasmo Research|publisher=ReefQuest|accessdate=6 May 2009|url=http://www.elasmo-research.org/education/ecology/deepsea-pacific_sleeper.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nDue to living in frigid depths, the sleeper shark's [[Shark liver oil|liver oil]] does not contain [[squalene]], which would solidify into a dense, nonbuoyant mass. Instead, the low-density compounds in the sharks' liver are diacylglyceryl ethers <!-- (DAGE) --> and [[Triglyceride|triacylglycerol]], which maintain their fluidity even at the lowest temperatures. Also, they store very little [[urea]] in their skin (like many deep sea sharks), but like other [[elasmobranch]]s, have high concentrations of urea and [[trimethylamine N-oxide|trimethylamine oxide]] (nitrogenous waste products) in their tissues as [[osmoprotectant]]s and to increase their [[buoyancy]].<ref name = \"Withers1994\">{{cite journal | last1 = Withers | first1 = P. C. | last2 = Morrison | first2 = G. | last3 = Guppy | first3 = M. | title = Buoyancy Role of Urea and TMAO in an Elasmobranch Fish, the Port Jackson Shark, ''Heterodontus portusjacksoni'' | journal = Physiological Zoology | volume = 67 | issue = 3 | pages = 693\u2013705 | date = May 1994 | jstor = 30163765 | doi=10.1086/physzool.67.3.30163765}}</ref> Trimethylamine oxide also serves to counteract the [[protein]]-[[protein folding#Disruption of the native state|destabilizing]] tendencies of [[urea#Laboratory uses|urea]]<ref name = Bennion2004>{{cite journal|last1=Bennion|first1=B. J.|last2= Daggett|first2= V.|title= Counteraction of urea-induced protein denaturation by trimethylamine N-oxide: a chemical chaperone at atomic resolution|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume= 101|issue= 17|date= 27 April 2004|pages= 6433\u20136438|doi= 10.1073/pnas.0308633101|pmid=15096583|pmc=404062}}</ref> and pressure.<ref name=\"Yancey2014\">{{cite journal|last1= Yancey|first1=P. H.|last2= Gerringer|first2=M. E.|last3= Drazen|first3=J. C.|last4= Rowden|first4=A. A.|last5= Jamieson|first5= A.|title= Marine fish may be biochemically constrained from inhabiting the deepest ocean depths|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume= 111|issue= 12|date= 2014-03-03|pages= 4461\u20134465|doi= 10.1073/pnas.1322003111|pmid=24591588|pmc=3970477}}</ref> Its presence in the tissues of both elasmobranch and [[teleost]] fish has been found to increase with depth.<ref name=\"Yancey2014\" /><ref name=\"Treberg2002\">{{cite journal|last1= Treberg|first1=J. R.|last2= Driedzic|first2=W. R.|title=Elevated levels of trimethylamine oxide in deep-sea fish: evidence for synthesis and intertissue physiological importance|journal= Journal of Experimental Zoology|volume= 293|issue= 1|date= 2002-05-30 |pages =39\u201345|doi= 10.1002/jez.10109|pmid=12115917}}</ref>\n\nBecause food is relatively scarce on the deep sea floor, the sleeper shark is able to store food in its capacious stomach. The sleeper shark's jaws are able to produce a powerful bite due to their short and transverse shape. The upper jaw teeth of the sleeper shark are spike-like, while the lower jaw teeth are oblique cusps and overlapping bases. This arrangement allows grasping and sawing of food too large to swallow. Pacific sleeper sharks have a short [[caudal fin]], which allows them to store energy for fast and violent bursts of energy to catch prey.<ref name=\"RQ\"/>\n\nIn 2015 a pacific sleeper shark was filmed near the Solomon Islands underneath an active volcano. The shark is able to survive in water with a high temperature and acidity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/794361/robots-investigate-sharks-living-underwater-volcano-solomon-islands|title=Mysterious sharks living INSIDE active underwater VOLCANO investigated by robots|first=Katie|last=Mansfield|date=20 April 2017|website=express.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=17&v=d79LoSLD8HU|title=Rarely Seen Shark Filmed Near Underwater Volcano - National Geographic|first=|last=National Geographic|date=8 July 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Known predators ==\nSleeper sharks are preyed on by the offshore ecotype of [[killer whale]]s off British Columbia.<ref name=\"The Canadian Press\">{{cite web|author=Keven Drews|author2=The Canadian Press|title=Killer whales feast on sharks off B.C. coast|publisher=The Canadian Press|accessdate=5 Sep 2011|url=http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110905/bc_killer_whales_eat_sharks_110905/20110905?hub=BritishColumbiaHome}}</ref> In addition, like the [[Greenland shark]], the parasitic [[copepod]] ''[[Ommatokoita elongata]]'' can often be observed consuming the shark's corneal tissue.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sharks}}\n* [[Greenland shark]]\n* [[List of sharks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;General references\n* {{ITIS |id=160610 |taxon=Somniosus pacificus |accessdate=23 January 2006}}\n* {{cite web | title=New giant squid predator found | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3370019.stm | accessdate=February 14, 2007 | work=BBC News | date=2004-01-08}}\n* Castro, Jose. \"Pacific Sleeper Sharks (Somniosus pacificus).\" Conservation Science Institute. 1983. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090513051928/http://conservationinstitute.org/ocean_change/predation/sleepershark.htm].\n* Martin, R. A. \"Pacific Sleeper Shark Bibliography.\" Biology of Sharks and Reys. ReefQuest Centre for Shark Research.[http://elasmo-research.org/education/ecology/biblio-pacific_sleeper.htm].\n* \"Megalodon caught on tape.\" My Paranormal Life. Google. [http://myparanormallife.blogspot.com/2006/11/megalodon-caught-on-tape.html]. (Erroneously-labelled footage of a sleeper shark)\n* Carroll, Amy. \"Sleeper Sharks: Awake and Hungry Sleeper sharks Not Culprits in Sea Lion Declines.\" Alaska Fish and Wildlife News. 1999. Alaska Department of Fish and Game.[http://www.wc.adfg.state.ak.us/index.cfm?adfg=wildlife_news.view_article&issue_id=26&articles_id=146].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/3370019.stm |date=January 8, 2004 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |title=New giant squid predator found |author=Paul Rincon}}\n* [http://www.oceanrecon.org/swf/sleeper_shark.swf ORCA Video of a sleeper shark]\n\n{{Selachimorpha|D.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q533894}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pacific sleeper shark}}\n[[Category:Somniosus]]\n[[Category:Fish of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Fish of the Arctic Ocean]]\n[[Category:Fish of Canada]]\n[[Category:Fish of Japan]]\n[[Category:Fish of Mexican Pacific coast]]\n[[Category:Fish of Russia]]\n[[Category:Fish of the Western United States]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Fauna of California]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Baja California Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Marine fish of Asia]]\n[[Category:Western North American coastal fauna]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1944]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of Asia]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Pacific sleeper shark\n| image = Pacific sleeper shark.png\n| status = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN\">{{Cite iucn | author = Ebert, D.A. | author2 = Goldman, K.J. | author3 = Orlov, A.M. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Somniosus pacificus'' | volume = 2009 | page = e.T161403A5416294 | date = 2009 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2009-2.RLTS.T161403A5416294.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Somniosus\n| species = pacificus\n| range_map = Somniosus pacificus distmap.png\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Pacific sleeper shark\n| authority = [[Henry Bryant Bigelow|Bigelow]] & [[William Charles Schroeder|Schroeder]], 1944\n| synonyms =\n| synonyms_ref =\n}}\n[[File:Somniosus pacificus noaa2.jpg|thumb|Pacific sleeper shark carcasses]]\nThe '''Pacific sleeper shark''' (''Somniosus pacificus'') is a [[sleeper shark]] of the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Somniosidae]], found in the North Pacific on [[continental shelves]] and slopes in [[Arctic]] and [[temperate]] waters between [[latitude]]s [[70th parallel north|70\u00b0N]] and [[22nd parallel north|22\u00b0N]], from the surface to {{convert|2000|m|ft}} deep.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/><ref name=fishbase>{{FishBase | genus = Somniosus | species =  pacificus | month = March| year = 2016}}</ref> Records from southern oceans are likely misidentifications of [[Somniosus|relatives]].<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> Its length is up to {{convert|4.4|m|ft|abbr=on}}, although it could possibly reach lengths in excess of {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=fishbase/>\n\n==Feeding habits==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2015}}\nPacific sleeper sharks, which are thought to be both predators and scavengers, can glide through the water with little body movement and little hydrodynamic noise, making them successful stealth predators. They feed by means of suction and cutting of their prey. They have large mouths that can essentially inhale prey and their teeth cut up any pieces that are too large to swallow. They show a characteristic rolling motion of the head when feeding. Only in [[Alaska]] has the shark's diet been studied - most sharks' stomachs contain remains of [[giant Pacific octopus]]. They are also known to feed on bottom-dwelling [[teleost]] fishes, as well as [[Sole (fish)|soles]], [[flounder]]s, [[Alaska pollock]], [[Sebastes|rockfishes]], [[shrimp]]s, [[hermit crab]]s, and even marine [[snail]]s. Larger Pacific sleeper sharks are also found to feed on fast-swimming prey such as [[squid]]s, [[Pacific salmon]], and [[harbor porpoise]]s. The diet of the Pacific sleeper shark seems to broaden as they increase in size. For example, a 3.7-m female shark found off [[Trinidad, California]] was found to have fed mostly on [[giant squid]]. Sleeper sharks found in Alaskan waters from {{convert|2|to|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} seem to feed mostly on flounder, pollock, and [[cephalopoda|cephalopods]], while sleeper sharks {{convert|3.3|to|4.25|m|ft|abbr=on}} long seem to consume teleosts and cephalopods, as well as [[marine mammal]]s. A recent study in the Gulf of Alaska suggests that sleeper sharks may prey on juvenile Steller sea lions.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Markus Horning|author2=Jo-Ann Mellish|last-author-amp=yes|title=In cold blood: evidence of Pacific sleeper shark (''Somniosus pacificus'') predation on Steller sea lions (''Eumetopias jubatus'') in the Gulf of Alaska|doi=10.7755/FB.112.4.6|year=2014|journal=Fishery Bulletin|volume=112|issue=4|pages=297\u2013310|url=http://ir.library.oregonstate.edu/xmlui/bitstream/1957/54605/1/HorningMarkusFisheriesWildlifeInColdBlood.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\nVery little is known about the early life of Pacific sleeper sharks. They are believed to produce eggs that hatch inside the female's body (reproduction is [[ovoviviparity|ovoviviparous]]), but gestation time is unknown and litter sizes are thought to be about 10 pups. Its length at birth is about {{convert|42|cm|ft|abbr=on}} or less.<ref name=\"RQ\"/>\n\n==Size==\nThe average mature size is {{convert|3.65|m|ft|abbr=on}} and {{convert|318|-|363|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. The largest Pacific sleeper shark verified in size measured {{convert|4.4|m|ft|abbr=on}} long and weighed {{convert|888|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, although it could possibly reach {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} or more.<ref name=fishbase/><ref name= Castro>Castro, Jos\u00e9 I., ''The Sharks of North America''. Oxford University Press (2011), {{ISBN|978-0-19-539294-4}}</ref> In 1989, an enormous Pacific sleeper shark was attracted to a bait in deep water outside [[Tokyo Bay]], [[Japan]] and filmed. The shark was estimated by [[Eugenie Clark]] to be about {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"RQ\">{{cite web|author=Martin, R. Aidan|title=Elasmo Research|publisher=ReefQuest|accessdate=6 May 2009|url=http://www.elasmo-research.org/education/ecology/deepsea-pacific_sleeper.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nDue to living in frigid depths, the sleeper shark's [[Shark liver oil|liver oil]] does not contain [[squalene]], which would solidify into a dense, nonbuoyant mass. Instead, the low-density compounds in the sharks' liver are diacylglyceryl ethers <!-- (DAGE) --> and [[Triglyceride|triacylglycerol]], which maintain their fluidity even at the lowest temperatures. Also, they store very little [[urea]] in their skin (like many deep sea sharks), but like other [[elasmobranch]]s, have high concentrations of urea and [[trimethylamine N-oxide|trimethylamine oxide]] (nitrogenous waste products) in their tissues as [[osmoprotectant]]s and to increase their [[buoyancy]].<ref name = \"Withers1994\">{{cite journal | last1 = Withers | first1 = P. C. | last2 = Morrison | first2 = G. | last3 = Guppy | first3 = M. | title = Buoyancy Role of Urea and TMAO in an Elasmobranch Fish, the Port Jackson Shark, ''Heterodontus portusjacksoni'' | journal = Physiological Zoology | volume = 67 | issue = 3 | pages = 693\u2013705 | date = May 1994 | jstor = 30163765 | doi=10.1086/physzool.67.3.30163765}}</ref> Trimethylamine oxide also serves to counteract the [[protein]]-[[protein folding#Disruption of the native state|destabilizing]] tendencies of [[urea#Laboratory uses|urea]]<ref name = Bennion2004>{{cite journal|last1=Bennion|first1=B. J.|last2= Daggett|first2= V.|title= Counteraction of urea-induced protein denaturation by trimethylamine N-oxide: a chemical chaperone at atomic resolution|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume= 101|issue= 17|date= 27 April 2004|pages= 6433\u20136438|doi= 10.1073/pnas.0308633101|pmid=15096583|pmc=404062}}</ref> and pressure.<ref name=\"Yancey2014\">{{cite journal|last1= Yancey|first1=P. H.|last2= Gerringer|first2=M. E.|last3= Drazen|first3=J. C.|last4= Rowden|first4=A. A.|last5= Jamieson|first5= A.|title= Marine fish may be biochemically constrained from inhabiting the deepest ocean depths|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume= 111|issue= 12|date= 2014-03-03|pages= 4461\u20134465|doi= 10.1073/pnas.1322003111|pmid=24591588|pmc=3970477}}</ref> Its presence in the tissues of both elasmobranch and [[teleost]] fish has been found to increase with depth.<ref name=\"Yancey2014\" /><ref name=\"Treberg2002\">{{cite journal|last1= Treberg|first1=J. R.|last2= Driedzic|first2=W. R.|title=Elevated levels of trimethylamine oxide in deep-sea fish: evidence for synthesis and intertissue physiological importance|journal= Journal of Experimental Zoology|volume= 293|issue= 1|date= 2002-05-30 |pages =39\u201345|doi= 10.1002/jez.10109|pmid=12115917}}</ref>\n\nBecause food is relatively scarce on the deep sea floor, the sleeper shark is able to store food in its capacious stomach. The sleeper shark's jaws are able to produce a powerful bite due to their short and transverse shape. The upper jaw teeth of the sleeper shark are spike-like, while the lower jaw teeth are oblique cusps and overlapping bases. This arrangement allows grasping and sawing of food too large to swallow. Pacific sleeper sharks have a short [[caudal fin]], which allows them to store energy for fast and violent bursts of energy to catch prey.<ref name=\"RQ\"/>\n\nIn 2015 a pacific sleeper shark was filmed near the Solomon Islands underneath an active volcano. The shark is able to survive in water with a high temperature and acidity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/794361/robots-investigate-sharks-living-underwater-volcano-solomon-islands|title=Mysterious sharks living INSIDE active underwater VOLCANO investigated by robots|first=Katie|last=Mansfield|date=20 April 2017|website=express.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=17&v=d79LoSLD8HU|title=Rarely Seen Shark Filmed Near Underwater Volcano - National Geographic|first=|last=National Geographic|date=8 July 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Known predators ==\nSleeper sharks are preyed on by the offshore ecotype of [[killer whale]]s off British Columbia.<ref name=\"The Canadian Press\">{{cite web|author=Keven Drews|author2=The Canadian Press|title=Killer whales feast on sharks off B.C. coast|publisher=The Canadian Press|accessdate=5 Sep 2011|url=http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110905/bc_killer_whales_eat_sharks_110905/20110905?hub=BritishColumbiaHome}}</ref> In addition, like the [[Greenland shark]], the parasitic [[copepod]] ''[[Ommatokoita elongata]]'' can often be observed consuming the shark's corneal tissue.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sharks}}\n* [[Greenland shark]]\n* [[List of sharks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;General references\n* {{ITIS |id=160610 |taxon=Somniosus pacificus |accessdate=23 January 2006}}\n* {{cite web | title=New giant squid predator found | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3370019.stm | accessdate=February 14, 2007 | work=BBC News | date=2004-01-08}}\n* Castro, Jose. \"Pacific Sleeper Sharks (Somniosus pacificus).\" Conservation Science Institute. 1983. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090513051928/http://conservationinstitute.org/ocean_change/predation/sleepershark.htm].\n* Martin, R. A. \"Pacific Sleeper Shark Bibliography.\" Biology of Sharks and Reys. ReefQuest Centre for Shark Research.[http://elasmo-research.org/education/ecology/biblio-pacific_sleeper.htm].\n* \"Megalodon caught on tape.\" My Paranormal Life. Google. [http://myparanormallife.blogspot.com/2006/11/megalodon-caught-on-tape.html]. (Erroneously-labelled footage of a sleeper shark)\n* Carroll, Amy. \"Sleeper Sharks: Awake and Hungry Sleeper sharks Not Culprits in Sea Lion Declines.\" Alaska Fish and Wildlife News. 1999. Alaska Department of Fish and Game.[http://www.wc.adfg.state.ak.us/index.cfm?adfg=wildlife_news.view_article&issue_id=26&articles_id=146].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/3370019.stm |date=January 8, 2004 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |title=New giant squid predator found |author=Paul Rincon}}\n* [http://www.oceanrecon.org/swf/sleeper_shark.swf ORCA Video of a sleeper shark]\n\n{{Selachimorpha|D.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q533894}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pacific sleeper shark}}\n[[Category:Somniosus]]\n[[Category:Fish of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Fish of the Arctic Ocean]]\n[[Category:Fish of Canada]]\n[[Category:Fish of Japan]]\n[[Category:Fish of Mexican Pacific coast]]\n[[Category:Fish of Russia]]\n[[Category:Fish of the Western United States]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Fauna of California]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Baja California Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Marine fish of Asia]]\n[[Category:Western North American coastal fauna]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1944]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of Asia]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of North America]]\n", "name_user": "Grammarspellchecker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSize", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacific_sleeper_shark"}
