{"title_page": "Long song", "text_new": "{{Expert needed|Music genres|talk=Section title goes here|date=March 2011}}\nThe '''long song''' ({{lang-mn|{{MongolUnicode|\u1824\u1837\u1832\u1820\u202f\u1822\u1822\u1828<br />\u1833\u1820\u182d\u1824\u1828}}}}, ''Urtiin duu'') is one of the central elements of the traditional [[music of Mongolia]]. This genre is called \"Long song\" not only because the songs are long, but also because each [[syllable]] of text is extended for a long duration. A four-minute song may only consist of ten words. Certain long songs such as '''''Uvgin shuvuu khoyor''''', also known as '''''Jargaltain delger''''' (lit. 'Old man and the Bird') has a length of up to 3 hours if to sing in full length with complete 32 stanzas. Lyrical themes vary depending on context; they can be philosophical, religious, romantic, or celebratory, and often use horses as a symbol or theme repeated throughout the song. Eastern Mongols typically use a [[Morin khuur]] (horse-head fiddle) as accompaniment, sometimes with a type of indigenous [[flute]], called ''limbe''. [[Oirats|Oirat]] groups of the Western Mongols traditionally sing long songs unaccompanied or accompanied with the [[Igil]].\n\nMongolian folk long song embraces a comprehensive nature of all national traditions and customs, including history, culture, aesthetics, ethics and philosophy. The main feature of the long song is the ''shuranhai'' (prolonged, [[tenuto]] notes with deeply modulated vibrato on the [[vowels]]). The Mongol aizam long songs are ancient grand songs that possess extensively broad vocal diapason and diverse [[extended technique|vocal movement techniques]], elaborate singing elements and [[musical improvisation|vocal improvisations]] such as ''dan'' (single) and ''davkhar'' (double) ''shurankhai'' (tenuto notes with deeply modulated [[vibrato]] on the vowels), ''nugalaa'' (sharp notes modulated in lower pitch), various vocal \u2018soothing\u2019 long-drawns, upward and downward ''usrelt'' ([[musical tone|tone]] leaps or sudden transmission to higher or lower tones), ''tsokhilgo'' ([[modulation (music)|vocal modulated]] pulsation), ''tsatslaga'' (sprinkling), ''khayalga'' (bestrewing or free improvised tone), ''shigshree'' (sifting or repeated vocal [[vibration]]) and other unique singing techniques.<ref>'Sunny Mongolia today' International magazine for Mongolian railway passengers, Issue #17. p.64-65. 2012]</ref> These features give the long song profound philosophical, meditational character, often depicting the spacious mountain valleys and a sense of tranquility, believed to represent the Mongolian soul.\n\nThree major styles are identified in long songs: ''besreg urtiin duu'' (\"minor long song\"), ''suman urtiin duu'' (\"ordinary long song\") and ''aizam urtiin duu'' (\"major' or majestic long songs\"). Again, the styles reflect the way of the performance of the ''shuranhai'' and other techniques rather than the sizes of the songs. The word \u2018Aizam\u2019 comes from the non-lexical [[vocable]] of \u2018Aya, zee khu\u2019 at the beginning of the grand long song, which features a broad melody with a context of philosophical theme, ceremony and quality of ode, honor, respect or solemnity. The ''aizam'' grand long songs are sung in a sequence at the beginning of a ceremony or feast, in accordance with the special ceremonial rules, and constitute the summit of the long songs which test the skills and capability of the singer and morin khuur (horse-headed fiddle) player.<ref>'Sunny Mongolia today' International magazine for Mongolian railway passengers, Issue #17. p.64-65. 2012]</ref>\n\n== Modern history ==\n\n[[UNESCO]] declared the Mongolian Long Song one of the [[Masterpieces of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity]] in 2005.\n\nOn April 12, 2013, the ''''''Mongolian Statehood Long Song'''''' was officially exalted at the Mongolian Statehood History Museum located in the State Ceremony Great Hall of the Government House of Mongolia.<ref>[http://www.24tsag.mn/content/30264.shtml News on the exaltation of Mongolian Statehood Long Song at the Statehood History Museum on Mongolian news site. Date April 12, 2012]</ref> ''''''Mongolian Statehood Long Song'''''' is an album of 9 Mongolian ''aizam'' (\"grande\") long songs, including '''''Ertnii saikhan''''' (\"Ancient Splendid\"), '''''Tumen Ekh '''''(\"Myriad's Leader\"), '''''Khuur Magnai''''' (\"Fiddle Leader\"), '''''Durtmal saikhan''''' (\"Iridescent Splendid\"), '''''Kherlengiin baraa''''' (\"Sight of Kherulen River\"), '''''Ikh Zambuutiviin naran''''' (Sun of Great Jambudvipa), '''''Asaryn undur''''' (\"Heavenly Noble\"), '''''Erkhem tur''''' (Statehood of Excellence) and '''''Enkh mendiin bayar''''' (\"Celebration of Welfare\").<ref>'Mongolian Statehood Long Song' Triple-CD album. Author: M.Dorjdagva. Translation by G.Delgermaa. 2013</ref> These songs were sung by [[Dorjdagva Myagmarsuren]], long song singer and researcher at the ''International Institute for the Study of Nomadic Civilizations''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nomadic.mn/ |title=IISNC Official website |access-date=2014-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001205233800/http://www.nomadic.mn/ |archive-date=2000-12-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Morin khuur musician is Battulga Batbold, one of the most proficient Morin khuur musicians at present. \nCreation of this album is the first and only edition of full-length Mongolian grand long songs almost lost during the socialist regime, when the long song was allowed to sing on stage only for 3\u20135 minutes. It did become a significant event in the history of Mongolian musicology, folk music tradition, cultural heritage and continuation and preservation of Mongolian classic art of long song, according to Mongolian renowned scholars, researchers, academicians and musicologists.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m9xxpBkA30Q%5D A TV program of Mongolian scholars valuing the importance of the 'Mongolian Statehood Long Songs' /in Mongolian/. Soon English subtitle will be available]</ref> The songs in the album feature singing in full-length (direct audio recording without any pause, music arrangement nor engineering), complete lyrics, authentic Mongolian singing techniques, different singing styles of Central Khalkha or Eastern Mongolia and Western Mongolia as well as ancient melody of each song restored on the basis of his research of a dozen years as well as accompaniment of authentic traditional Morin khuur with leather-cover and horse-hair strings.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/pages/%D0%9C%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%BB-%D1%82%D3%A9%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%B9%D0%BD-%D1%83%D1%80%D1%82%D1%8B%D0%BD-%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%83/1456122651327090 'Mongolian Statehood Long Song' Official Facebook page] /in Mongolian/ English page coming soon by Dec 1, 2014</ref> \nThe total length of the 9 long songs are 258 minutes in total, each song with a length of 25\u201335 minutes. The single edition of Mongolian Statehood Long Song encased in a wooden case inlaid with Nine Jewels is donated to, registered and kept at the State Intangible Heritage Fund of National Cultural Heritage Center of Mongolia.<ref>[http://monheritage.mn/mn/news/News.aspx Cultural Heritage Center of Mongolia under the Culture, Sports and Tourism Ministry of Mongolia. Official site]</ref> In September, 2014, the album of '''Mongolian Statehood Long Song''' by M.Dorjdagva was released publicly with the support of the Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism of Mongolia<ref>[http://mcst.gov.mn/ Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism of Mongolia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129052951/http://mcst.gov.mn/ |date=2014-11-29 }}</ref> and the Arts and Culture Development Foundation of Mongolia.\n\nMusic researcher Ojuna W. Pilcher has published several studies of the long song in the region of [[Alxa League]] in [[Inner Mongolia]]. She has observed that the long song today expresses a nostalgia of the past after modernization, and \u201cvisual and zoological metaphors connected to the nomadic lifestyle are not only highly significant to urtyn duu\u2019s song texts, categorization, and singing technique but are also closely related to ornamentation, the achievement of vocal timbre, the singers\u2019 understanding of nomadic herding life, and their feelings of longing and nostalgia as expressed through the music.\u201d<ref>PILCHER, Ojuna W., \u201c\u2018You Can\u2019t Sing\nUrtyn Duu If You Don\u2019t Know How to Ride a Horse\u2019: Urtyn Duu in Alshaa, Inner Mongolia,\u201d ''Asian Music'', 2018, pp. 4\u201333.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bao, Darkhan, and Wuyuntaoli (2007). ''Mongolian Long Song''. Hangzhou: Zhejiang People\u2019s  Publishing House.\n* Carrizo,  Liliana (2010).  \u201cUrtyn Duu: Performing Musical Landscapes and the Mongolian Nation.\u201d Master's  thesis, University  of Illinois  at Urbana-Champaign. \n* Chao, David (2010).  \u201cUrtyn Duu: The Mongolian Long Song in  Mongolia  and China.\u201d PhD diss., University  of California.\n* Pegg, Carole (2001). ''Mongolian Music, Dance & Oral Narrative: Performing Diverse Identities''. Seattle: University of Washington Press.\n* Pilcher, Ojuna W. (2018). \u201c\u2018You Can\u2019t Sing Urtyn Duu If You Don\u2019t Know How to Ride a Horse\u2019: Urtyn Duu in Alshaa, Inner Mongolia,\u201d ''Asian Music'', 2018, pp. 4\u201333.\n* Yoon,  Sunmin (2011). \u201cChasing the Singers: The Transition  of  Long Song (Urtyn Duu) in  Post-socialist Mongolia.\u201d  PhD diss., University  of Maryland.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Music}}\n* [http://www.unesco.org/culture/intangible-heritage/25apa_uk.htm UNESCO: Urtiin Duu: Traditional Folk Long Song]\n* [http://www.urtynduu.mn/index.php/en-us/ Mongolian Long Song Project]\n{{Mongolia topics}}\n{{UNESCO Oral and Intangible music}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Song}}\n[[Category:Mongolian traditional music]]\n[[Category:Masterpieces of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expert-subject|Music genres|talk=Section title goes here|date=March 2011}}\nThe '''long song''' ({{lang-mn|{{MongolUnicode|\u1824\u1837\u1832\u1820\u202f\u1822\u1822\u1828<br />\u1833\u1820\u182d\u1824\u1828}}}}, ''Urtiin duu'') is one of the central elements of the traditional [[music of Mongolia]]. This genre is called \"Long song\" not only because the songs are long, but also because each [[syllable]] of text is extended for a long duration. A four-minute song may only consist of ten words. Certain long songs such as '''''Uvgin shuvuu khoyor''''', also known as '''''Jargaltain delger''''' (lit. 'Old man and the Bird') has a length of up to 3 hours if to sing in full length with complete 32 stanzas. Lyrical themes vary depending on context; they can be philosophical, religious, romantic, or celebratory, and often use horses as a symbol or theme repeated throughout the song. Eastern Mongols typically use a [[Morin khuur]] (horse-head fiddle) as accompaniment, sometimes with a type of indigenous [[flute]], called ''limbe''. [[Oirats|Oirat]] groups of the Western Mongols traditionally sing long songs unaccompanied or accompanied with the [[Igil]].\n\nMongolian folk long song embraces a comprehensive nature of all national traditions and customs, including history, culture, aesthetics, ethics and philosophy. The main feature of the long song is the ''shuranhai'' (prolonged, [[tenuto]] notes with deeply modulated vibrato on the [[vowels]]). The Mongol aizam long songs are ancient grand songs that possess extensively broad vocal diapason and diverse [[extended technique|vocal movement techniques]], elaborate singing elements and [[musical improvisation|vocal improvisations]] such as ''dan'' (single) and ''davkhar'' (double) ''shurankhai'' (tenuto notes with deeply modulated [[vibrato]] on the vowels), ''nugalaa'' (sharp notes modulated in lower pitch), various vocal \u2018soothing\u2019 long-drawns, upward and downward ''usrelt'' ([[musical tone|tone]] leaps or sudden transmission to higher or lower tones), ''tsokhilgo'' ([[modulation (music)|vocal modulated]] pulsation), ''tsatslaga'' (sprinkling), ''khayalga'' (bestrewing or free improvised tone), ''shigshree'' (sifting or repeated vocal [[vibration]]) and other unique singing techniques.<ref>'Sunny Mongolia today' International magazine for Mongolian railway passengers, Issue #17. p.64-65. 2012]</ref> These features give the long song profound philosophical, meditational character, often depicting the spacious mountain valleys and a sense of tranquility, believed to represent the Mongolian soul.\n\nThree major styles are identified in long songs: ''besreg urtiin duu'' (\"minor long song\"), ''suman urtiin duu'' (\"ordinary long song\") and ''aizam urtiin duu'' (\"major' or majestic long songs\"). Again, the styles reflect the way of the performance of the ''shuranhai'' and other techniques rather than the sizes of the songs. The word \u2018Aizam\u2019 comes from the non-lexical [[vocable]] of \u2018Aya, zee khu\u2019 at the beginning of the grand long song, which features a broad melody with a context of philosophical theme, ceremony and quality of ode, honor, respect or solemnity. The ''aizam'' grand long songs are sung in a sequence at the beginning of a ceremony or feast, in accordance with the special ceremonial rules, and constitute the summit of the long songs which test the skills and capability of the singer and morin khuur (horse-headed fiddle) player.<ref>'Sunny Mongolia today' International magazine for Mongolian railway passengers, Issue #17. p.64-65. 2012]</ref>\n\n== Modern history ==\n\n[[UNESCO]] declared the Mongolian Long Song one of the [[Masterpieces of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity]] in 2005.\n\nOn April 12, 2013, the ''''''Mongolian Statehood Long Song'''''' was officially exalted at the Mongolian Statehood History Museum located in the State Ceremony Great Hall of the Government House of Mongolia.<ref>[http://www.24tsag.mn/content/30264.shtml News on the exaltation of Mongolian Statehood Long Song at the Statehood History Museum on Mongolian news site. Date April 12, 2012]</ref> ''''''Mongolian Statehood Long Song'''''' is an album of 9 Mongolian ''aizam'' (\"grande\") long songs, including '''''Ertnii saikhan''''' (\"Ancient Splendid\"), '''''Tumen Ekh '''''(\"Myriad's Leader\"), '''''Khuur Magnai''''' (\"Fiddle Leader\"), '''''Durtmal saikhan''''' (\"Iridescent Splendid\"), '''''Kherlengiin baraa''''' (\"Sight of Kherulen River\"), '''''Ikh Zambuutiviin naran''''' (Sun of Great Jambudvipa), '''''Asaryn undur''''' (\"Heavenly Noble\"), '''''Erkhem tur''''' (Statehood of Excellence) and '''''Enkh mendiin bayar''''' (\"Celebration of Welfare\").<ref>'Mongolian Statehood Long Song' Triple-CD album. Author: M.Dorjdagva. Translation by G.Delgermaa. 2013</ref> These songs were sung by [[Dorjdagva Myagmarsuren]], long song singer and researcher at the ''International Institute for the Study of Nomadic Civilizations''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nomadic.mn/ |title=IISNC Official website |access-date=2014-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001205233800/http://www.nomadic.mn/ |archive-date=2000-12-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Morin khuur musician is Battulga Batbold, one of the most proficient Morin khuur musicians at present. \nCreation of this album is the first and only edition of full-length Mongolian grand long songs almost lost during the socialist regime, when the long song was allowed to sing on stage only for 3\u20135 minutes. It did become a significant event in the history of Mongolian musicology, folk music tradition, cultural heritage and continuation and preservation of Mongolian classic art of long song, according to Mongolian renowned scholars, researchers, academicians and musicologists.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m9xxpBkA30Q%5D A TV program of Mongolian scholars valuing the importance of the 'Mongolian Statehood Long Songs' /in Mongolian/. Soon English subtitle will be available]</ref> The songs in the album feature singing in full-length (direct audio recording without any pause, music arrangement nor engineering), complete lyrics, authentic Mongolian singing techniques, different singing styles of Central Khalkha or Eastern Mongolia and Western Mongolia as well as ancient melody of each song restored on the basis of his research of a dozen years as well as accompaniment of authentic traditional Morin khuur with leather-cover and horse-hair strings.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/pages/%D0%9C%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%BB-%D1%82%D3%A9%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%B9%D0%BD-%D1%83%D1%80%D1%82%D1%8B%D0%BD-%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%83/1456122651327090 'Mongolian Statehood Long Song' Official Facebook page] /in Mongolian/ English page coming soon by Dec 1, 2014</ref> \nThe total length of the 9 long songs are 258 minutes in total, each song with a length of 25\u201335 minutes. The single edition of Mongolian Statehood Long Song encased in a wooden case inlaid with Nine Jewels is donated to, registered and kept at the State Intangible Heritage Fund of National Cultural Heritage Center of Mongolia.<ref>[http://monheritage.mn/mn/news/News.aspx Cultural Heritage Center of Mongolia under the Culture, Sports and Tourism Ministry of Mongolia. Official site]</ref> In September, 2014, the album of '''Mongolian Statehood Long Song''' by M.Dorjdagva was released publicly with the support of the Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism of Mongolia<ref>[http://mcst.gov.mn/ Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism of Mongolia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129052951/http://mcst.gov.mn/ |date=2014-11-29 }}</ref> and the Arts and Culture Development Foundation of Mongolia.\n\nMusic researcher Ojuna W. Pilcher has published several studies of the long song in the region of [[Alxa League]] in [[Inner Mongolia]]. She has observed that the long song today expresses a nostalgia of the past after modernization, and \u201cvisual and zoological metaphors connected to the nomadic lifestyle are not only highly significant to urtyn duu\u2019s song texts, categorization, and singing technique but are also closely related to ornamentation, the achievement of vocal timbre, the singers\u2019 understanding of nomadic herding life, and their feelings of longing and nostalgia as expressed through the music.\u201d<ref>PILCHER, Ojuna W., \u201c\u2018You Can\u2019t Sing\nUrtyn Duu If You Don\u2019t Know How to Ride a Horse\u2019: Urtyn Duu in Alshaa, Inner Mongolia,\u201d ''Asian Music'', 2018, pp. 4\u201333.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bao, Darkhan, and Wuyuntaoli (2007). ''Mongolian Long Song''. Hangzhou: Zhejiang People\u2019s  Publishing House.\n* Carrizo,  Liliana (2010).  \u201cUrtyn Duu: Performing Musical Landscapes and the Mongolian Nation.\u201d Master\u2019s  thesis, University  of Illinois  at Urbana-Champaign. \n* Chao, David (2010).  \u201cUrtyn Duu: The Mongolian Long Song in  Mongolia  and China.\u201d PhD diss., University  of California.\n* Pegg, Carole (2001). ''Mongolian Music, Dance & Oral Narrative: Performing Diverse Identities''. Seattle: University of Washington Press.\n* Pilcher, Ojuna W. (2018). \u201c\u2018You Can\u2019t Sing Urtyn Duu If You Don\u2019t Know How to Ride a Horse\u2019: Urtyn Duu in Alshaa, Inner Mongolia,\u201d ''Asian Music'', 2018, pp. 4\u201333.\n* Yoon,  Sunmin (2011). \u201cChasing the Singers: The Transition  of  Long Song (Urtyn Duu) in  Post-socialist Mongolia.\u201d  PhD diss., University  of Maryland.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Music}}\n* [http://www.unesco.org/culture/intangible-heritage/25apa_uk.htm UNESCO: Urtiin Duu: Traditional Folk Long Song]\n* [http://www.urtynduu.mn/index.php/en-us/ Mongolian Long Song Project]\n{{Mongolia topics}}\n{{UNESCO Oral and Intangible music}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Song}}\n[[Category:Mongolian traditional music]]\n[[Category:Masterpieces of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_song"}
{"title_page": "Turn Off the News (Build a Garden)", "text_new": "{{italic title|all=yes}}\n{{Infobox album\n| italic_title = no\n| name       = <i>Turn Off the News (Build a Garden)</i>\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real]]\n| cover      = Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real Turn Off the News (Build a Garden).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 14, 2019\n| recorded   = 2018\u20132019\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]\n| length     = 51:13\n| label      = [[Fantasy Records]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Turn Off the News (Build a Garden)''''' is the fifth [[studio album]] by American [[country rock]] band [[Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real]]. The album was released on June 14, 2019, by [[Fantasy Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/turn-off-the-news-build-a-garden/1460038337 |title=Turn Off the News (Build a Garden) by Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real on Apple Music |publisher=Music.apple.com |date= |accessdate=2019-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Doyle |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lukas-nelson-promise-of-the-real-new-album-neil-young-829232/ |title=Lukas Nelson and Promise of the Real Announce New Album With Guests |publisher=Rollingstone.com |date=2019-05-01 |accessdate=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 76/100<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/turn-off-the-news-build-a-garden/lukas-nelson-promise-of-the-real |title=Turn Off the News, Build a Garden by Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real Reviews and Tracks |publisher=Metacritic |date= |accessdate=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[AllMusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/turn-off-the-news-build-a-garden-mw0003274306 |title=Turn Off the News, Build a Garden - Lukas Nelson, Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Horowitz |first=Hal |url=https://americansongwriter.com/2019/06/lukas-nelson-promise-of-the-real-turn-off-the-news-build-a-garden/ |title=Lukas Nelson & Promise of the Real: Turn Off the News (Build A Garden) |publisher=Americansongwriter.com |date=2019-06-11 |accessdate=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev3Score = 6.0/10<ref>{{cite web|author=Evan Rytlewski |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lukas-nelson-and-promise-of-the-real-turn-off-the-news-build-a-garden/ |title=Lukas Nelson / Promise of the Real: Turn Off the News (Build a Garden) Album Review |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2019-06-21 |accessdate=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Turn Off the News (Build a Garden)'' received generally positive reviews from critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from critics, the album received an average score of 76, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\", based on 10 reviews.<ref name=\"metacritic1\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album has sold 16,100 copies in the United States as of October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2019/10/43981-top-10-country-albums-pure-sales-chart-for-october-7-2019|title=Top 10 Country Albums: Pure Sales Chart for October 7, 2019|work=RoughStock|first=Matt |last=Bjorke |date= October 7, 2019 |accessdate=October 19, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 51:13\n\n| title1 = Bad Case\n| length1 = 4:39\n\n| title2 = Turn Off the News (Build a Garden)\n| length2 = 3:43\n\n| title3 = Where Does Love Go\n| length3 = 3:43\n\n| title4 = Save a Little Heartache\n| length4 = 3:09\n\n| title5 = Lotta Fun\n| length5 = 2:57\n\n| title6 = Civilized Hell\n| length6 = 4:50\n\n| title7 = 